---
description: Enforce test-first for any behaviour change; never implement without a test
alwaysApply: true
---

# Test first, then implement

When you are about to **add or change behaviour** (frontend or backend):

1. **First:** Add or update a test that specifies the expected outcome. Run the
   test; it should fail (or be red) until the behaviour exists.
2. **Then:** Implement the code so the test passes.
3. **Do not** implement new or changed behaviour and only add a test afterward.
   If you already implemented, add the test in the same change and treat the
   work as incomplete until the test exists and passes.

Applies to: new or changed UI (pages, components), API client helpers, API
endpoints, DB/CLI behaviour. Use the frontend-development skill for frontend,
rust-backend-workflow for backend; this rule makes the order (test then code)
mandatory.

**Styling-only changes are exempt from adding tests.** Purely visual work (CSS,
typography, spacing, colors, layout classes, design tokens in `layout.css`) does
**not** require automated tests. TDD and behavioural tests still apply when you
change **behaviour** (what the user can do, what data appears, navigation,
validation, API usage). See **frontend-development**.
